<article id="node-16993">
<h1 >3.4.5.80 Continuation &amp; Termination of PLS</h1>
<h2>Summary</h2>
<p>The following table lists the circumstances in which payment of loans under <a href="../../../acronyms#pls" title="Pension loans scheme">PLS</a> may change.</p>
<table><thead><tr><th scope="col">The PLS loan isâ¦</th>
<th scope="col">If the recipientâ¦</th>
</tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>terminated,</td>
<td>
<ul><li>reaches their maximum loan amount, OR</li>
<li>becomes not qualified for the pension or allowance upon which their PLS qualification is based, OR</li>
<li>withdraws from the scheme.</li>
</ul></td>
</tr><tr><td>suspended,</td>
<td>
<ul><li>has their pension or allowance suspended.</li>
</ul></td>
</tr><tr><td>reviewed for possible change,</td>
<td>
<ul><li>marries, or becomes a member of a couple (<a href="../../../1/1/m/120">1.1.M.120</a>), OR</li>
<li>separates from their partner, OR</li>
<li>sells some real estate.</li>
</ul></td>
</tr></tbody></table><p>If necessary, these circumstances are explained in more detail in the rest of this topic. Repayment of the loan is explained in another topic.</p>
<div class="reference">
<p><strong>Policy reference:</strong> SS Guide <a href="90">3.4.5.90</a> Repayment of the PLS Loan</p>
</div>
<h2>Maximum loan amount</h2>
<p>If a PLS recipient's debt exceeds their maximum loan amount, then he/she ceases to participate in the scheme from the beginning of the first instalment period, for his/her pension or allowance, that begins after the debt exceeds the maximum loan.</p>
<div class="reference">
<p><strong>Act reference:</strong> <a href="https://www.legislation.gov.au/Series/C2004A04121" title="Social Security Act 1991">SSAct</a> section 1141 Person ceases to participate in pension loans scheme if debt exceeds maximum loan available</p>
</div>
<h2>Loss of qualification for pension/allowance</h2>
<p>A recipient is no longer qualified for PLS if they lose qualification for the pension that qualifies them for PLS. Payments under the scheme cease from the same date as the pension ceases.</p>
<p>If the pension is suspended, the loan under PLS, as well as the pension is not paid during the suspended period. The payments under PLS will recommence when the pension is restored.</p>
<div class="reference">
<p><strong>Policy reference:</strong> SS Guide <a href="10">3.4.5.10</a> Qualification for PLS</p>
</div>
<h2>Withdrawal from the scheme</h2>
<p>A recipient may withdraw from the scheme at any time, and the debt can be repaid:</p>
<ul><li>immediately, OR</li>
<li>from the person's estate upon their death. Interest will continue to accrue on the debt until it is fully recovered.</li>
</ul><div class="reference">
<p><strong>Act reference:</strong> <a href="https://www.legislation.gov.au/Series/C2004A04121" title="Social Security Act 1991">SSAct</a> section 1142 Person withdraws from pension loans scheme</p>
</div>
<h2>Sale of real estate</h2>
<p>PLS ceases to apply to a recipient if:</p>
<ul><li>they sell a parcel of real estate of significant value, AND</li>
<li>the value of the secured real estate falls below what is a reasonable amount in the Age component amount table.</li>
</ul><p>The delegate needs to consider the circumstances of the case when deciding whether the debt should be immediately repaid. If the debt is still safely secured by the remaining real estate, the delegate may exercise their discretion in removing the charge over the disposed real estate without taking recovery action.</p>
<div class="reference">
<p><strong>Act reference:</strong> <a href="https://www.legislation.gov.au/Series/C2004A04121" title="Social Security Act 1991">SSAct</a> section 1135A(3) The following is the Tableâ¦</p>
</div>
<h2>Person marries or becomes a member of a couple</h2>
<p>If a recipient marries or becomes a member of a couple, their qualification and rate must be reviewed.</p>
<div class="example">
<p><strong>Explanation:</strong> A review is necessary to ensure the recipient is still qualified for PLS.</p>
</div>
<div class="example">
<p><strong>Example:</strong> The couple may now have different assets as a result of the new partner bringing assets into the marriage, the value of the recipient's assets being reduced or the new partner's intentions, if any, to apply under PLS.</p>
</div>
<h2>Separation</h2>
<p>If a PLS recipient separates from their partner, their circumstances must be reviewed.</p>
<div class="example">
<p><strong>Explanation:</strong> This will establish:</p>
<ul><li>whether the asset/s securing the debt is affected by a property settlement, and</li>
<li>what impact this may have on continuing qualification under the scheme, and</li>
<li>the eventual recovery of the debt.</li>
</ul></div>
<p>If the separation is permanent, and one member of the couple is no longer entitled to receive payments under PLS, the debt owed by that person may be recovered in part or in full:</p>
<ul><li>when the property settlement occurs, OR</li>
<li>at an appropriate time dependent on the circumstances of the case.</li>
</ul><div class="example">
<p><strong>Example:</strong> A person who no longer qualifies because they are under age pension age or have insufficient assets to secure the debt.</p>
</div>
<p>If the separation is permanent and both people wish to continue in the scheme, then each member of the couple will need to qualify for payments under PLS in their own right.</p>
<h2>Reviews</h2>
<p>If a person qualifies for PLS, reviews are conducted on the same basis as reviews for the pension/allowance they receive or are qualified for. PLS recipients have the appeal rights associated with the pension or allowance they are receiving.</p>
<div class="reference">
<p><strong>Policy reference:</strong> SS Guide <a href="../../../6/1">6.1</a> Changes in Income &amp; Assets - Reviews, <a href="../../../6/2/3">6.2.3</a> Retirement &amp; Widows Reviews</p>
</div>
</article>	<div id="view-last-reviewed-date">
		
		  
